  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Record of the Guest House at Yeongdeok
  author: Kwon Geun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Yeongdeok sits upon the sea's far edge, a place most remote and desolate. Long ravaged by pirates' incursions, the people fled and hid themselves away, leaving villages as empty ruins for many years. Only when walls were raised and settlers gathered back did the scattered remnants gradually return, finding some measure of peace in their livelihoods. Once, while traveling in exile, I passed through this place and found no official residence erected—the county magistrate's own dwelling was but a few thatched huts, low and cramped, no better in appearance than the homes of common folk.

    In the autumn of the seventh year of Hongwu, there came from Gyerim a gentleman named Lee Inshil, who took office as magistrate here. Through his diligent governance and judicious rulings, the entire county soon gained renown for order and justice. He consulted with the townspeople about constructing a proper public hall. The following winter, timber was felled from the mountains. Come spring, when rains swelled the streams, the logs were floated down the waterway and arrived at the town's foundation without need for laborious carrying. Thus was erected a courthouse with chambers arranged to the left and right, its gates and corridors, kitchens and stables all in proper place. Moreover, where no well had existed within the walls, one was dug, and clear, cold water sprang forth—pure enough to drink. All the people of that county rejoiced together.

    A magistrate's hall serves to receive travelers and administer the law—no greater work exists in governance. A well provides for daily necessity and guards against calamity—no more pressing matter attends a community. That Magistrate Lee gave such diligent attention to these concerns shows he knew well which duties come first. A local gentleman scholar, Kim Jeok, came to study with me in the capital and requested that I record these accomplishments. Hearing of them, I could not but admire and praise such wise stewardship.

    —Twenty-sixth year of Hongwu, in the mid-autumn of the year Gyeyu
  footnotes:
    - 'Yeongdeok: A county in present-day South Korea, historically vulnerable to Japanese pirate raids (倭寇) during the medieval period.'
    - 'Hongwu: The reign period of the first Ming emperor (1368-1398).'
    - 'Gyerim (鷄林): An ancient name for the Korean peninsula, here referring to Korea.'
    - The author, Kwon Geun (權近, 1352-1409), was a prominent Joseon official and scholar who experienced political exile, which is referenced in this record.
